OK yes, I think I will try this. Of course I will have fot it in with 
the current strategy of lowering a species&#39; fitness afetr a period of no 
improvements - which amounts to culling stagnant species. I think this 
culling is important because it ultimately allows us to give up on a 
species and allocate search time to the remaining species. So I will 
track # of generations since last improvement, when it reaches some 
threshold, if the &#39;ok to prune&#39; flag is set then enter a prune phase, 
otherwise cull the species.

So during the pruning phase we should track, say, the average number of 
connection and neuron genes in the species. If this does not drop for 
some fixed number of generations (say 3 or 4) then the pruning phase is 
over, we set the pruning flag to false ( so that it wont happen again). 
And now if we reach the stagnation threshold again, then the species 
gets culled.

What I would like to do then is try this out on a new problem domain, 
one that is fast to simulate but difficult enough to pose a challenge to 
NEAT as it stands. Any suggestions? Perhaps the tic-tac-toe domain would 
be good, because the limited number of game moves means the simulations 
won&#39;t take up too much CPU time as the search progresses.  Another 
possibilty that I think I mentioned before is character recognition. 
Ideally a &#39;sexy&#39; domain would be good too for PR purposes :)

